That little bit of alliteration was as much of an attempt to mask the tedium of this journey as it was a tribute to the wonders of ice, which are perhaps more phenomenal than any that spring from the power of rhyme.

Whether it’s driving or flying, the saga of transportation in the Antarctic really is quite extraordinary. How else would you explain that Estelle van Gorp and I were seated in a plane with just over a dozen men in Arctic gear, under the open clear sky of a Wesminster afternoon, watching one of the most romantic destinations in the world? A destination that does not sport the runways at Gatwick Airport.

The time capsule that is Keswick island airport appears to time warp back to the sixties. The runway (if it can be called that) is only a two hundred meter strip of land that is quite possible prone to the vagaries of the weather system. Little wonder then, that in December 2015, when Machiel Erik De Swaan flew in to attend the SUNY Downstate Singapore Delegation, the weather was not good enough to land at Keswick.

Instead, De Swaan had to be flown in an hour southwards to Cairns, the nearest international airport (the Australians have only going an extra mile to land at one of the most picturesque destinations in the world).
